📌 Project Overview

Today's lab focused on troubleshooting a Linux network service that had become inaccessible over a custom TCP port. 
Although the Apache HTTP service was configured to use the correct port and appeared to be running, remote clients were unable to establish a connection.

The objective was to identify the root cause using Linux networking and system administration tools, restore service accessibility, and verify connectivity from a 
remote jump host while preserving the server's security posture.

Objectives
Diagnose why an Apache web service was unreachable on a custom port.
Verify Apache service status and configuration.
Confirm the web server was listening on the expected port.
Test network connectivity between hosts.
Investigate Linux firewall rules.
Restore secure access to the application.
Validate connectivity using curl.
Environment
Component	Description
Operating System	Linux
Web Server	Apache (httpd)
Client	Jump Host
Target Server	App Server 1 (stapp01)
Apache Port	6400
Problem Statement

The monitoring system reported that the Apache web service on App Server 1 was unreachable via port 6400.

Although the service itself might have been down, the issue could also have originated from networking, firewall rules, or server configuration.

Expected verification:

curl http://stapp01:6400
Troubleshooting Process
1. Verify Apache Service Status

Checked whether the Apache service was running.

sudo systemctl status httpd

Initially, Apache failed to start due to an Address already in use error.

2. Identify Port Conflicts

Verified which processes were listening on network ports.

sudo ss -tulpn

After correcting the Apache configuration, the service successfully listened on:

*:6400
3. Verify Apache Configuration

Confirmed Apache was configured to listen on the required port.

grep -R "^Listen" /etc/httpd/conf/httpd.conf

Output:

Listen 6400
4. Test Local Connectivity

Verified the service responded locally.

curl http://localhost:6400

The page loaded successfully, confirming Apache itself was functioning correctly.

5. Test Remote Connectivity

From the Jump Host:

curl http://stapp01:6400

Received:

curl: (7) Failed to connect
No route to host

This indicated the request never reached Apache and suggested a networking or firewall issue.

6. Inspect Firewall Rules

Since firewalld was not installed, I inspected the active iptables rules.

sudo iptables -L -n

Discovered the INPUT chain contained:

REJECT all -- anywhere anywhere reject-with icmp-host-prohibited

No rule existed permitting inbound traffic on TCP port 6400.

7. Allow Access to Port 6400

Inserted an ACCEPT rule before the REJECT rule.

sudo iptables -I INPUT 5 -p tcp --dport 6400 -j ACCEPT

Verified the rule:

sudo iptables -L -n
8. Validate the Fix

From the Jump Host:

curl http://stapp01:6400

The Apache webpage was successfully returned, confirming the issue had been resolved.

